                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Secrets Exposed</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2000-04-24</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Ethical influence has rarely been dealt with so carefully, credibly and intelligently. The blend of NLP with solid research from social psychology and the author's personal experience make this a fascinating read. My only concern about the Psychology of Persuasion is that this book seems to reveal too many sociological and interpersonal communication "secrets." One hopes that the book buyer will follow Hogan's admonition to make sure every communciation is really a Win/Win or No Deal. The book is top notch and should be owned by anyone in business, sales or marketing. I think the section on brainwashing could have been more extensive. It is already a great self defense tool against cults but expansion on key ideas would have made it even more invaluable. I thought the master persuader chapters were some of the most advanced material I've seen. The book was relatively easy to read and the exercises added to my understanding of the more complex strategies. The discussion about values alone was probably worth the price of the book.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Powerful in Print and in Person</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
